**Answer: B (25 cm)**

Second overtone of closed pipe = 5th harmonic = \frac{5v}{4L_c}

Third harmonic of open pipe = \frac{3v}{2L_o} = \frac{3v}{2 \times 30} = \frac{v}{20}

Setting equal: \frac{5v}{4L_c} = \frac{v}{20}

4L_c = 5 \times 20 = 100

L_c = 25 \text{ cm}

**Answer: B (2:1)**

Fundamental of open pipe: f_{open} = \frac{v}{2L}

Fundamental of closed pipe: f_{closed} = \frac{v}{4L}

Ratio: \frac{f_{open}}{f_{closed}} = \frac{v/2L}{v/4L} = \frac{4L}{2L} = 2

So f_{open} : f_{closed} = 2 : 1

An open pipe of the same length has a fundamental frequency twice that of a closed pipe.

**Answer: B (550 Hz)**

Source approaching, observer stationary:

f' = f \times \frac{v}{v - v_s} = 500 \times \frac{330}{330 - 30}

f' = 500 \times \frac{330}{300} = 500 \times 1.1 = 550 \text{ Hz}

When the source approaches, the wavelength is compressed and the observer hears a higher frequency.

**Answer: B (4)**

Beat frequency = |f_1 - f_2| = |256 - 260| = 4 \text{ beats per second}

The beats are clearly audible since 4 Hz is well within the human perception limit (~8 Hz). The resultant sound alternates between loud and soft 4 times every second.

**Answer: D (0.60 m)**

The distance between a node and the nearest antinode = \frac{\lambda}{4}

\frac{\lambda}{4} = 0.15 \text{ m}

\lambda = 4 \times 0.15 = 0.60 \text{ m}

Recall: node-to-node = \lambda/2, node-to-antinode = \lambda/4.

**Answer: C (v\sqrt{2})**

v = \sqrt{\frac{T}{\mu}}

New speed: v' = \sqrt{\frac{4T}{2\mu}} = \sqrt{\frac{2T}{\mu}} = \sqrt{2} \times \sqrt{\frac{T}{\mu}} = v\sqrt{2}

Speed depends on the square root of the ratio T/mu. Quadrupling tension and doubling mu gives a net factor of sqrt(2).

**Answer: C (566 Hz)**

f = \frac{1}{2L}\sqrt{\frac{T}{\mu}}

New frequency: f' = \frac{1}{2(L/2)}\sqrt{\frac{2T}{\mu}} = \frac{1}{L}\sqrt{\frac{2T}{\mu}}

= 2 \times \frac{1}{2L} \times \sqrt{2} \times \sqrt{\frac{T}{\mu}} = 2\sqrt{2} \times f

f' = 2\sqrt{2} \times 200 = 2 \times 1.414 \times 200 \approx 566 \text{ Hz}

**Answer: C (362 m/s)**

v \propto \sqrt{T} (absolute temperature)

\frac{v_{50}}{v_0} = \sqrt{\frac{T_{50}}{T_0}} = \sqrt{\frac{273 + 50}{273}} = \sqrt{\frac{323}{273}} = \sqrt{1.183}

\sqrt{1.183} \approx 1.088

v_{50} = 332 \times 1.088 \approx 361 \text{ m/s}

Closest option is 362 m/s.
